# Server
PORT=3000
# Listen host. 0.0.0.0 = all interfaces (Docker default). On a bare-metal deploy
# behind Caddy, set 127.0.0.1 so the port isn't exposed to the internet directly
# (the deploy script does this). The server trusts X-Forwarded-For from the proxy.
# HOST=127.0.0.1
WEBHOOK_SECRET=change-me-to-a-long-random-secret
WS_PATH=/ws
# Track history + entity snapshot are held IN MEMORY only — no database, no
# data volume. State is lost on restart (empty map until live data arrives).
# How long to keep in-memory track history before pruning (duration shorthand: ms|s|m|h|d, or a bare ms integer).
HISTORY_RETENTION=7d

# CORS (Phase 7) — off/same-origin by default (recommended: the Caddy/D2
# deploy serves web + API from one origin, so this stays unset in production
# too). Set to a comma-separated allow-list of origins (or "*") only if the
# web build is served from a different origin than this API.
# CORS_ORIGIN=https://hud.example.com

# Static serving (Phase 7) — set to 'true' to have this Fastify server serve
# the built web/dist (index.html + chase.html) directly, so one container
# can run web + API + WS behind Caddy (the Dockerfile sets this by default).
# Leave 'false' for local dev (Vite dev server serves the web app instead).
SERVE_STATIC=false
# Override the directory served when SERVE_STATIC=true (defaults to
# ../web/dist relative to the server package; the Docker image sets this to
# an absolute in-image path — see Dockerfile).
# STATIC_ROOT=/app/web/dist

# SondeHub radiosonde poller — comma-separated serials (e.g. "Y0322352,Y0322353").
# Empty by default: no poller starts on boot (default map stays empty; live-only).
SONDEHUB_SERIALS=
# Poll interval in ms for each configured SondeHub serial.
SONDEHUB_POLL_MS=15000

# ADS-B poller — optional, off by default. Set to 'true' AND provide ADSB_URL
# (a local dump1090/tar1090 aircraft.json endpoint) to enable.
ENABLE_ADSB=false
# ADSB_URL=http://localhost:8080/data/aircraft.json
# ADSB_POLL_MS=5000

# Web (Vite — must be prefixed VITE_ to be exposed to client code)
# WebSocket URL. Optional: the HUD defaults to a SAME-ORIGIN ws(s)://<host>/ws
# (works in dev via the Vite /ws proxy and in production behind Caddy). Only set
# this to override for a cross-origin API.
# VITE_WS_URL=ws://localhost:3000/ws
# HTTP origin of the server API (GET /history/:id trail hydration; POST /chaser
# from chase mode — see below). Leave unset for same-origin:
# vite.config.ts proxies /history and /chaser to localhost:3000 in dev, and
# production (Caddy, or SERVE_STATIC=true) serves web + API from the same
# origin. Only set this if the API truly lives on a different origin — and
# set CORS_ORIGIN above to match, or the cross-origin browser fetch will fail.
# VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:3000

# Chase mode: open the HUD with ?chase=<name> (e.g.
# https://your-host/?chase=Team1) on the chaser's phone/tablet. That device
# reads navigator.geolocation.watchPosition and POSTs fixes to POST /chaser
# (unauthenticated — trusted-network-only, see chaser-route.ts) as chaser
# "<name>", and centers its own recovery ring. Without ?chase= the HUD is a
# pure viewer. Requires HTTPS in the field (or localhost) — geolocation is
# blocked on plain HTTP.

# --- Docker Compose / Caddy (Phase 7 deploy, D2) ---
# Only used by docker-compose.yml + Caddyfile, not by the server process
# itself. Your public domain (Caddy auto-issues/renews a TLS cert for it).
# For a local/no-DNS smoke test, use ':80' instead (plain HTTP, no TLS).
# LAZYMAPHUD_DOMAIN=hud.example.com
